COVID-19 Analysis¶

This is the companion code for the data scientist blog project

There are 3 datasets used in this project sourced from below:¶

https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/tree/master/csse_covid_19_data

The data is downloaded as of 03/07/2020 CST

This analysis is aiming at answering following questions of interest: ¶

  1. How many phases of infections there are in the observed virus trasimission process?

  2. Does the virus transmit similarly in different areas/states?

  3. How is the situation in China now at 3 months after the outbreak? Will it get cleared soon?

  4. How long it will take to see the panic outbreak in the US and when it will clear out?

There are a few things needs to be addressed here:¶

  1. These 3 datasets are wide format, but for forecasting/modeling I need the long format, so I will need to transpose these 3 data
  1. Confirmed case, cured case and death cases are in separate files and I will need to merge them together into 1 file
  1. There are many countries and regions in the dataset, for this analysis, I will only focus on US and Mainland China </font>
In [524]:
# Transpose
df1 = df1.melt(id_vars=['Province/State', 'Country/Region', 'Lat', 'Long'],
               var_name='updateDate', value_name='confirmed')
df2 = df2.melt(id_vars=['Province/State', 'Country/Region', 'Lat', 'Long'],
               var_name='updateDate', value_name='death')
df3 = df3.melt(id_vars=['Province/State', 'Country/Region', 'Lat', 'Long'],
               var_name='updateDate', value_name='recovered')

In [533]:
def plot_group(data, x, y, group, time, measure, title):
    '''
    This is to visualize the time trend of confirmed/recovered/death counts by group for this project
    data: dataframe containing the data, need to have updateDate, group, and measure columns
    x, y: plot size 
    group: group by variable
    measure: tracking varaible, can be confirmed, recovered, or death
    title_text: title for the plot 
    '''
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(x,y))
    for key, grp in data.groupby(group):
        ax.plot(grp[time], grp[measure], label=key)

    plt.title(title)    
    ax.legend()
    plt.show()
In [534]:

__Above two plots indicate the spreading of COVID-19 is a sigma shape curve, which means we could use some survival / non-linear models to describe its behavior and make predictions.__ ¶

This answers Question 1, there are roughly 3 phases in the transimission process:

  • Discovery phase ( first a couple weeks), confirmed cases slowly increase, probably limited by the diagnose capability
  • Exploding phase ( following 2-3 weeks), confirmed cases fast increase, likeyly majority of the infected patients get diagnosed
  • Stable phase ( starting 1 month afterwords): confirmed case plateaud out, probably because of prevention/isolation takes effects and the virus starts getting under control </font>

Figure 2 of China COVID-19 Time Trend by Province answers Question 2:

  • Different province in China all have similar S-shape trends, so it is reasonable to assume US virus spreading will follow the same trend, hence, we could use data in China to estimate US phases and times </font>

Now checking death and recovered cases to estimate current situations in China¶

In [535]:
def plot_covid(data, x, y, title_text):
    '''
    This is to visualize the time trend of confirmed/recovered/death counts for this project
    data: dataframe containing the data, need to have updateDate, confirmed, recovered, death columns
    x, y: plot size 
    title_text: title for the plot
    '''
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
    ax1.set_ylabel('Confirmed | Recovered Count')
    ax1.plot(data['updateDate'], data['recovered'], color='green')
    ax1.plot(data['updateDate'], data['confirmed'], color='blue')
    ax1.legend()

    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    ax2.set_ylabel('Death Count', color='red')
    ax2.plot(data['updateDate'], data['death'], color='red')
    ax2.legend(loc='center left')

    plt.title(title_text)
    plt.show()

Above Figure 3 and Figure 5 can answer Question 3:¶

  • Out of Hubei ( Figure 5 ), confirmed case is plateaued out, recovered case is still increasing and the gap is starting to close out; death case shows a similar sigma shape and starts to reach the plateau
  • For Hubei ( Figure 3 ), confirmed case still shows a tiny upward slope, recovered case is increasing, however, only a little more than half of confirmed case is recovered, death case is still increasing

Overall, it appears the COVID-19 spreading in China will get under control soon out of Hubei; For Hubei, a couple more months will be needed before things go back to normal

Some notes about US curent situation (Figure 7): ¶

  • There is almost no recovered cases - This actually makes sense because only 2 states (CA, WA) are in the exploding phase shown in Figure 6, and the rest are still in discovery phase, and based on overall China (Figure 5), it takes about 3 weeks before the recovered case picking up
  • Both overall China (Figure 5) and Hubei (Figure 3) show the death curve rate is shallower compared to confrimed curve. However, the US curve disagrees on that as evidenced by the cross of blue and red curve in Figure 7. This may be caused by small sample size/data noise, it is alo possibly caused by incorrectly evaluation of current situation. Until a few days ago, CDC only recommends checking for COVID-19 for cases directly related to China, or other severly impacted countries/regions. So it is possible that he virus has already spreaded out, but not diagnosed/confirmed. Which means the above confirmed curve is biased and there will be large jumps in the next a couple weeks when those people are diagnosed and confirmed. At that time, the recovered and death curve should have a similar trend as in China. </font>

Let's try to find some province in China that look like US to estimate

  • how long will take the US to get panic outbreak (the mid point of the exploding phase)

  • how long it will take to break out (the starting of the plateau phase) </font>

Assume US virus spreading will be somewhere between Guangdong and Hunan, now it is time to fit the Guangdong and Hunan curve to get parameter estimates for us ¶

In [544]:
def func(x, a, b, c):
    '''
    This is the functionn form of S curve
    x: days from the beginning
    a, b, c: parameters
    '''
    return a / (b + np.exp(-c*x))
In [550]:
# fitting Guangdong
dd1 = df_new3[df_new3['state']=='Guangdong']
plt.plot(dd1['days'], dd1['confirmed'], 'b-', label='Guangdong COVID-19 Actual Confirmed')
popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, dd1['days'], dd1['confirmed'])
plt.plot(dd1['days'], func(dd1['days'], *popt), 'r--', label='fit: a=%5.3f, b=%5.3f, c=%5.3f' % tuple(popt))

# Fitting US

# Convert the forecast days back to calendar days
enddate=dd3['updateDate'].max() + pd.DateOffset(1)
# Populate missing with 1 day after the max day then correct forwards
dd3['updateDate'] = dd3['updateDate'].fillna(value = enddate)
dd3['offday'] = dd3['days']-current_end
dd3.loc[(dd3['updateDate']<enddate), 'offday']=0

dd3['forecastDate'] = dd3['updateDate'] + pd.to_timedelta(dd3['offday'], unit='D')
